2010, etc.) follows Special Agent Tom White and his assistants as they track the killers of one extended Osage family through a closed local culture of greed, bigotry, and lies in pursuit of protection for the survivors and justice for the dead. But he doesn't stop there; relying almost entirely on primary and unpublished sources, the author goes on to expose a web of conspiracy and corruption that extended far wider than even the FBI ever suspected. This page-turner surges forward with the pacing of a true-crime thriller, elevated by Grann's crisp and evocative prose and enhanced by dozens of period photographs. Dogged original research and superb narrative skills come together in this gripping account of pitiless evil. 76 Pub Date: April 18, 2017 ISBN: 978-0-385-53424-6 Page Count: 352 Publisher: Doubleday Review Posted Online: Feb. 1, 2017 Kirkus Reviews Issue: Feb. 15, 2017 Categories: GENERAL HISTORY | TRUE CRIME | UNITED STATES | FIRST/NATIVE NATIONS | HISTORY Share your opinion of this book More by David Grann BOOK REVIEW THE <i>WAGER</i> by David Grann BOOK REVIEW KILLERS OF THE FLOWER MOON by David Grann BOOK REVIEW THE LOST CITY OF Z by David Grann More About This Book BOOK TO SCREEN Brendan Fraser Joins Cast of ‚ÄòFlower Moon‚Äô Film BOOK TO SCREEN Oct. 20 Release For 'Killers of the Flower Moon' BOOK TO SCREEN ‚ÄòKillers of the Flower Moon‚Äô: Out of Focus BOOK LIST 20 Books for Serious Foodies 36 Reviews NONFICTION shop now amazon bookshop bookshelf NIGHT by Elie Wiesel & 
                    translated by Marion Wiesel ‚Äß RELEASE DATE: Jan. 16, 2006 The author's youthfulness helps to assure the inevitable comparison with the Anne Frank diary although over and above the... bookshelf shop now amazon bookshop Elie Wiesel spent his early years in a small Transylvanian town as one of four children. He was the only one of the family to survive what Francois Maurois, in his introduction, calls the "human holocaust" of the persecution of the Jews, which began with the restrictions, the singularization of the yellow star, the enclosure within the ghetto, and went on to the mass deportations to the ovens of Auschwitz and Buchenwald. There are unforgettable and horrifying scenes here in this spare and sombre memoir of this experience of the hanging of a child, of his first farewell with his father who leaves him an inheritance of a knife and a spoon, and of his last goodbye at Buchenwald his father's corpse is already cold let alone the long months of survival under unconscionable conditions. The author's youthfulness helps to assure the inevitable comparison with the Anne Frank diary although over and above the sphere of suffering shared, and in this case extended to the death march itself, there is no spiritual or emotional legacy here to offset any reader reluctance. 36 Pub Date: Jan. 16, 2006 ISBN: 0374500010 Page Count: 120 Publisher: Hill & Wang Review Posted Online: Oct. 7, 2011 Kirkus Reviews Issue: Jan. 15, 2006 Categories: BIOGRAPHY & MEMOIR | HOLOCAUST | HISTORY | GENERAL BIOGRAPHY & MEMOIR | GENERAL HISTORY Share your opinion of this book More by Elie Wiesel BOOK REVIEW FILLED WITH FIRE AND LIGHT by Elie Wiesel ; 
